trans-unit.source: Scientific models of complex water resource systems help us understand and experiment with the behavior of those systems. Most scientific modeling today requires the use of software that can be hard to understand, expensive to build and maintain, and present little online access. Many of these challenges can be tackled through the use of software that bridges the capabilities of water resource system modeling and the needs of water resource stakeholders.

trans-unit.source: The goal of the SWIM project is to advance water sustainability research capabilities through the integration, execution and interpretation of water models and participatory reasoning processes. Using the meaning of data and models, SWIM facilitates interpretations of water availability in the US Southwest and North of Mexico for stakeholder-driven analysis from the socio-environmental perspective.

trans-unit.source: The Water Balance Model has a focus on simplicity, with the goal being to help stakeholders understand how changes in climate could influence regional water availability. The water balance model simulates surface water reservoir storage, reservoir releases and storage in groundwater aquifers in the project study area. The project study area includes portions of New Mexico (NM, US), Texas (TX, US), and Chihuahua (CH, MX). The model simulates storages of water through a simple accounting based on storages at the beginning of a simulation period and inflows and outflows throughout the simulation period.
trans-unit.target: The Water Balance Model has a focus on simplicity, with the goal being to help stakeholders understand how changes in climate could influence regional water availability. The water balance model simulates surface water reservoir storage, reservoir releases and storage in groundwater aquifers in the project study area. The project study area includes portions of New Mexico (NM, US), Texas (TX, US), and Chihuahua (CH, MX). The model simulates storages of water through a simple accounting based on storages at the beginning of a simulation period and inflows and outflows throughout the simulation period.

trans-unit.source: The model simulates future time periods, using time series inputs for (a) local precipitation and temperature and (b) San Marcial gauge flows. Demands for surface water releases from Caballo Reservoir are assumed to be the maximum available under the Rio Grande Project 2008 Operating Agreement, which bases releases on water stored in Elephant Butte and Caballo reservoirs and treaty and compact requirements for sharing water between TX (US), NM (US), and CH (MX). Demands from groundwater aquifers are calculated using a base rate of groundwater pumping from each aquifer, based on historical pumping rates, combined with a variable rate, based on historical replacement of surface water shortages with groundwater pumping.
trans-unit.target: The model simulates future time periods, using time series inputs for (a) local precipitation and temperature and (b) San Marcial gauge flows. Demands for surface water releases from Caballo Reservoir are assumed to be the maximum available under the Rio Grande Project 2008 Operating Agreement, which bases releases on water stored in Elephant Butte and Caballo reservoirs and treaty and compact requirements for sharing water between TX (US), NM (US), and CH (MX). Demands from groundwater aquifers are calculated using a base rate of groundwater pumping from each aquifer, based on historical pumping rates, combined with a variable rate, based on historical replacement of surface water shortages with groundwater pumping.

trans-unit.source: Explore predefined questions of interest, created with input from stakeholders, and see how SWIM can help you answer them. A canned scenario makes a choice of which model to use, what scenario to use, and chooses of what outputs to display based on the relevance to the question. These include river storage and flow, groundwater levels, urban prices, consumption, and climate impacts on crops. You can further customize a scenario, if needed.

trans-unit.source: For this canned scenario, select the total cumulative loss on the Hueco Bolson and Mesilla Bolson. Note that the climate only directly affects the surface. It can be observed that the loss is much steeper than the recharge on both aquifers. SWIM provides a visual representation of the outcomes of the scenario without requiring additional software. In addition, you can interchange the units used for the visualizations and compare output variables side-by-side.

trans-unit.source: The SWIM interface makes available a set of scientific models which you can customize using scenarios to project into the future. SWIM includes predefined scenarios to get you started; each predefined scenario defines the value for one or many input parameters of the model. Models have predefined scenarios grouped in categories, e.g., climate, technology and recovery.
trans-unit.target: The SWIM interface makes available a set of scientific models which you can customize using scenarios to project into the future. SWIM includes predefined scenarios to get you started; each predefined scenario defines the value for one or many input parameters of the model. Models have predefined scenarios grouped in categories, e.g., climate, technology and recovery.

trans-unit.source: Step 1: On the main navigation bar, place your pointer over the Models dropdown menu. A list of scientific models will be displayed. For this tutorial, select the Water Balance Model.
trans-unit.target: Step 1: On the main navigation bar, place your pointer over the Models dropdown menu. A list of scientific models will be displayed. For this tutorial, select the Water Balance Model.

trans-unit.source: A landing page with infomation about the model will be displayed. To access the customization workflow, press the Create Scenario button located in the banner at the top of the page.
trans-unit.target: A landing page with infomation about the model will be displayed. To access the customization workflow, press the Create Scenario button located in the banner at the top of the page.

trans-unit.source: The customization workflow is a three-step process: Scenario Selection, Run Model and View Results.
trans-unit.target: The customization workflow is a three-step process: Scenario Selection, Run Model and View Results.

trans-unit.source: Step 2: On the Select Scenarios step of the workflow, you can select one predefined scenario from each category. To select a scenario, press the representative image of the scenario. For this tutorial select a scenario combination from each category as follows: Climate - "Extreme Stress", Evaporation - "Default", and Reservoir Operation - "Minimum reservoir storage at 20% of capacity".
trans-unit.target: Step 2: On the Select Scenarios step of the workflow, you can select one predefined scenario from each category. To select a scenario, press the representative image of the scenario. For this tutorial select a scenario combination from each category as follows: Climate - "Extreme Stress", Evaporation - "Default", and Reservoir Operation - "Minimum reservoir storage at 20% of capacity".

trans-unit.source: Step 3: Browse back to the climate scenarios. Each scenario contains a small description and a link for additional information. Press the Learn More... hyperlink. A popup box will be displayed. This box shows the defined values for the model parameters when selecting this scenario. Click on the Affected Model Inputs dropdown and select SanMarIn. The name, description and data plot of this input will be displayed. The units of the data values can be changed on the convert units dropdown menu.
trans-unit.target: Step 3: Browse back to the climate scenarios. Each scenario contains a small description and a link for additional information. Press the Learn More... hyperlink. A popup box will be displayed. This box shows the defined values for the model parameters when selecting this scenario. Click on the Affected Model Inputs dropdown and select SanMarIn. The name, description and data plot of this input will be displayed. The units of the data values can be changed on the convert units dropdown menu.

trans-unit.source: Step 4 (optional): To further customize a scenario, the model's individual input parameters can be accesed through the Input Catalog (located on the top-right of the page). This catalog contains a listing of editable and non-editable input parameters. As an example, access the Inflows at San Marcial Gauges and press over the table row. A detailed view of the input will be displayed. The parameter values can be directly modified on the data table, and visualized as a line plot or bar plot.
trans-unit.target: Step 4 (optional): To further customize a scenario, the model's individual input parameters can be accesed through the Input Catalog (located on the top-right of the page). This catalog contains a listing of editable and non-editable input parameters. As an example, access the Inflows at San Marcial Gauges and press over the table row. A detailed view of the input will be displayed. The parameter values can be directly modified on the data table, and visualized as a line plot or bar plot.

trans-unit.source: Step 5: Go back to the select scenarios screen. Press the green Run Model button. A dialog box will be displayed with a Model Run Form. First, input a name for your custom scenario. Second, select your water-related role (i.e., what role identifies you when creating this scenario). Third, click on the Scenario Description text box. This text box will automatically include the information about the predefined scenario(s) used. Additional text can be included. Finally, you are required to agree with the website policies to run your model. You can learn more about these policies by clicking on the provided links. Once the form is complete, the Submit button will be enabled.
trans-unit.target: Step 5: Go back to the select scenarios screen. Press the green Run Model button. A dialog box will be displayed with a Model Run Form. First, input a name for your custom scenario. Second, select your water-related role (i.e., what role identifies you when creating this scenario). Third, click on the Scenario Description text box. This text box will automatically include the information about the predefined scenario(s) used. Additional text can be included. Finally, you are required to agree with the website policies to run your model. You can learn more about these policies by clicking on the provided links. Once the form is complete, the Submit button will be enabled.

trans-unit.source: The results of executing your scenario will be available after a few seconds. The page automatically shows the View Results step once results are available. In contrast to the canned scenarios, the complete list of the model outputs is available to review.
trans-unit.target: The results of executing your scenario will be available after a few seconds. The page automatically shows the View Results step once results are available. In contrast to the canned scenarios, the complete list of the model outputs is available to review.
